  "school": "ICT",
  "definition": "The cyclical phases price moves through: Expansion (large directional move with shallow pullbacks, often forming FVG), Retracement (slow shallow pullback against trend, often into FVG/OB), Consolidation (range-bound oscillation), and Reversal (expansion met with opposing expansion). These phases repeat fractally across time frames, and identifying the current phase dictates whether to anticipate continuation, reversal, or wait for manipulation out of a range.",
  "identification_rules": [
    "Expansion: price rapidly breaks prior swing high/low with large-bodied candles closing beyond prior candle ranges, small wicks, shallow opposing pullbacks, often forming FVG; no deep retracements.",
    "Retracement: slow shallow pullback against prevailing expansion, failing to close outside prior candle ranges; confirm termination by failure swings on opposing side (no sweep of prior swing high/low).",
    "Consolidation: price oscillates between defined high and low without closing beyond either extreme; candles have small bodies, no directional expansion.",
    "Reversal: expansion met with opposing expansion, often forming higher time frame wick; confirmed by change in state of delivery (closing back through series of opposing candles) or SMT divergence at point of interest.",
    "Phase transitions confirmed by candle 2 or 3 closure on working time frame and change in state of delivery on lower time frame; let additional candles print if direction unclear.",
    "After three or more consecutive expansion candles delivering into liquidity, anticipate phase transition to consolidation or reversal.",
    "Within consolidation, wait for sweep of range high/low before entering; sweep followed by aggressive opposing expansion signals reversal, while shallow retracement suggests extreme will be revisited.",
    "Distinguish retracement from reversal: counter-move aggressive (expansion-like) = reversal; slow/shallow = retracement.",
    "Apply fractally across all time frames; anchor transitions to new candle opens on higher time frames.",
    "Expansion respects equilibrium (0.5) on its side; if not, flip bias expectation.",
    "Use CSD to confirm phase transition, forming protected swing."
  ],
  "trading_implication": "Identify current phase to determine entry strategy and bias. In Expansion, favor continuation trades from shallow retracements into PD arrays; avoid fading active expansion. After multiple expansion candles into liquidity, wait for new phase (Consolidation or Reversal). In Consolidation, wait for sweep of range high/low before entering toward opposite extreme. Confirmed Reversals via CSD allow positioning for new trend. Apply fractally across time frames, aligned with higher time frame bias to filter trades and set targets.",
  "common_mistakes": [
    "Confusing retracement with reversal: retracement is slow/shallow, reversal is aggressive opposing expansion.",
    "Confusing consolidation with retracement: consolidation is sideways, retracement is directional pullback.",
    "Expecting deep retracements during expansion phase instead of recognizing expansions only provide shallow pullbacks.",
    "Entering immediately after large expansion candle or multiple expansion periods without waiting for new phase to develop.",
    "Acting on reversal-looking candle without waiting for candle 2 closure or CSD to confirm phase transition.",
    "Trading against in-progress expansion candle instead of waiting for it to close and reversal candle to form.",
    "Looking for entries inside consolidation rather than waiting for sweep of range high/low to form protected swing.",
    "Continuing to trade in direction of expansion after three or more consecutive expansion candles into liquidity.",
    "Trading phase transitions without aligning to higher time frame bias or ignoring higher time frame targets.",
    "Treating consolidation as reversal/accumulation and entering before clear breakout or sweep of range extreme.",
    "Trading reversals off irrelevant swing points or before actual relevant extreme has been swept.",
    "Failing to adjust protected swing when reversal signs appear, leaving prior protected low/high vulnerable.",
    "Not waiting for enough candle closure to confirm phase transition, leading to inducement.",
    "Only looking at single time frame, ignoring correspondence between higher and lower time frame phases.",
    "Chasing after three expansions without recognizing new consolidation or retracement phase starting.",
    "Ignoring equilibrium respect in expansion; failing to use it as bias flip trigger.",
    "Trading reversal at random highs/lows instead of relevant swing points or prior highs/lows.",
    "Not cross-validating with related assets: consolidation may fail due to SMT divergence."
  ],
